                Hussman Fund's Highest-Performing Total Return Mutual Fund (HSTRX)            


    By Jea Yu | June 17, 2016 — 8:00 AM EDT    






Share
























































Hussman Funds manages four long-term investment funds. The founder, Dr. John P. Hussman, personally invests most of his liquid assets into the Hussman funds. Most of the board of directors invest significant portions of their assets in Hussman Funds as well. The top total return fund is the Hussman Strategic Total Return Fund ("HSTRX"). The fund invests primarily in conservative fixed-income instruments, including bonds, U.S. Treasury bonds, Strips, mortgage-backed securities (MBS) and investment-grade corporate debt rated BBB or higher by Standard and Poor's (S&P) and Moody's Investors Service Inc.
The fund may invest up to 30% of assets internationally in precious metals, mining stocks, energy securities, real estate investment trusts (REITs) and exchange-traded-funds (ETFs), as well as foreign commodities, currencies and government debt. The fund has $448 million in assets and generated a 4.93% average annual return (AAR) since inception on Sept. 12, 2002, as of March 31, 2016. The fund has a 0.66% expense ratio, with a $1,000 minimum initial investment and $500 for an individual retirement account (IRA).
The following is a closer look into the Hussman Strategic Total Return Fund.
Bond Holdings
The fund holdings fall into two main categories: bonds and stocks. The bond portion has a 50.21% allocation in government debt and 49.39% allocation in cash with 0.40% allocated to corporate debt. Of the bond investments, 95.36% are invested in the United States, 0.62% in Japan and 0.37% in France. The top five bond holdings are U.S. Treasury Notes 2.50% at 12.90%, U.S. Treasury Notes 1.5% at 12.64%, U.S. Treasury Notes 2.125% at 6.22% and U.S. Treasury Notes at 2.00% of total assets.
Stock Holdings
Of the stock holdings, the fund has a 98.27% weighting in the basic materials sector, followed by 1.56% in utilities and 0.17% in energy. The top five stock holdings are Newmont Mining (NYSE: NEM) with 3.17%, Barrick Gold Corp. Inc. (NYSE: ABX) with 3.16%, Goldcorp Inc. (NYSE: GG) with 2.26%, Agnico Eagle Mines Ltd. (NYSE: AEM) with 2.15% and United States Oil ETF (NYSEARCA: USO) with 1.80% of total assets. These holdings demonstrate the heavy appetite that the Hussman Strategic Total Return Fund has for tangible basic materials and energy-related equity investments. The conservative fixed-income products in the bond holdings offset the more volatile yet opportunistic returns from the precious metals and crude oil industries.
Market Outlook
Interestingly, Dr. John P. Hussman, president of Hussman Investment Trust, stated in his May 23, 2016, weekly market comment, "We currently estimate that the total return for a conventional portfolio mix of stocks, bonds and Treasury bills (60/30/10) is likely to average scarcely 1.5% annually over the coming decade." Hussman is a stark opponent of the Federal Reserve's zero-interest rate policy and insists "The Fed has done enormous violence to the public, and to the underlying stability of the financial markets, not only by encouraging a reckless yield-seeking financial bubble as the response to the global financial crisis that resulted from the previous Fed-induced yield seeking bubble; not only driving the financial markets to the point where pool long-term returns and wicked interim losses are inevitable, but also by creating an environment where scarce savings have been increasingly diverted to speculative activities…" Hussman expects the S&P 500 "to lose about 40-55% over the completion of this cycle…," which would only be a "run-of-the-mill outcome" based on history.
Performance
The mix has performed well, as the year-to-date (YTD) return is 10.03%, compared to the S&P 500 index return of 1.10%. The one-year performance was 6.67%, compared to negative 1.54% for the S&P 500, as of May 23, 2016. With improving energy prices and a rising interest rate environment, the Hussman Strategic Total Return Fund is strategically positioned to benefit from both catalysts, with its unique mix of bonds and energy and materials stocks.









  






 









STOCKS: 
HSTRX, NEM, ABX 




































